if rollercoaster tycoon did not exist it would be necessary to invent him - or - i'm sure all those POV shots were cool at the time. Love the specific form of incandescently 70s detective on display here, he just feels right.

We've seen a lot of action movies deliberately trying to ape video game aesthetics but this is probably the closest the form has ever gotten. Huge chunks of this movie look, alternatingly, like Mortal Kombat, Far Cry, Uncharted, and, oddly enough, Skyrim. It's a better movie about gaming than Neveldine & Taylor's Gamer - it too has its fair share of Crank-isms but instead of meth'd out chaos it has a more formalist structural dedication to boss fights, slow-mo wall vaulting, and level transitions. It's stunning. I want to turn on Playstation right NEEOWWWW

I cannot fathom the amount of intentionality that has to have gone into making something this unfunny. It's so soul-stealingly awful and that is coming from someone who usually eats shit like this up. It's not sublimely stupid or ironically stupid or so stupid it's good. It's just stupid. The only thing I can say for it is that the baseline for jokes is so low that when the odd mildly funny thing happens it hits like manna from heaven and oh god you could cry. Queer duck must appear before a criminal tribunal

In taking away the aesthetic stability of the scary church setting they forced themselves to give the Nun a new impetus for terrorizing random europeans and so instead of being a passive-aggressive haunt, she is now on a continent spanning quest to secure the catholic dragonballs so she can go super-saiycred. The final confrontation reminded me of the joker boss battle from Arkham Asylum that everyone hates. She has a ground-spike attack
